ress looks for that file and, if found, uses it.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><code>page-{slug}.php</code>¬†‚Äî</strong>¬†If no custom template has been assigned,¬†WordPress looks for and uses¬†a specialized template that contains the¬†page‚Äôs slug.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><code>page-{id}.php</code>¬†‚Äî</strong>¬†If a specialized¬†template that includes the page‚Äôs slug is not found,¬†WordPress looks for and uses a specialized template named with the page‚Äôs ID.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><code>page.php</code>¬†‚Äî</strong>¬†If a specialized template that includes the page‚Äôs ID is not found,¬†WordPress looks for and uses the theme‚Äôs default page template.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><code>index.php</code>¬†‚Äî</strong>¬†If no specific page templates are assigned or found, WordPress defaults back to using the theme‚Äôs index file to render pages.</li>\r\n</ol>','Astringent','','inherit','closed','closed','','50-revision-v1','','','2016-08-01 11:39:46','2016-08-01 11:39:46','',50,'http://dickinsons.dev/uncategorized/50-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(84,1,'2016-08-01 11:40:15','2016-08-01 11:40:15','<h2 id=\"uses-for-page-templates\" class=\"toc-heading\" tabindex=\"-1\">Uses for Page Templates #<span class=\"screen-reader-text\">Uses for Page Templates</span></h2>\r\nPage templates display your¬†site‚Äôs dynamic content on a page, e.g., posts, news updates, calendar events, media files, etc. You¬†may decide that you want your homepage to look a specific way, that is quite different to other¬†parts of your site. Or, you may want to display a featured image that links to a post on one part of the page, have a list of latest posts elsewhere, and use a custom navigation. You can use page templates to achieve¬†these things.\r\n\r\nThis section shows you how to build page templates that can be selected by your users through their admin screens.\r\n\r\nFor example, you can build page templates for:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>full-width, one-column</li>\r\n 	<li>two-column with a sidebar on the